08670nam a22020055i 9780691236339DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021052571  a97806912363397 a10.1515/97806912363392doi  a(DE-B1597)623972  a(OCoLC)1338019746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aGN281 4aGN281b.B438 2022 7aSCI0270002bisacsh04a599.93/8223/eng/202112011 aBellwood, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Five-Million-Year Odyssey :bThe Human Journey from Ape to Agriculture /cPeter Bellwood. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b25 b/w illus. 6 tables. 21 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1 The Odyssey Revealed -- t2 The Odyssey Begins -- t3 Out of Africa -- t4 New Species Emerge -- t5 The Mysterious Newcomer -- t6 Stretching the Boundaries -- t7 How Food Production Changed the World -- t8 Homelands of Plant and Animal Domestication -- t9 Voices from the Deep Past -- t10 The Fertile Crescent and Western Eurasia -- t11 Asia-Pacific Adventures -- t12 Africa, Australia, and the Americas -- t13 Ape to Agriculture -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tA NOTE ON THE TYPE0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe epic story of human evolution, from our primate beginnings more than five million years ago to the agricultural eraOver the course of five million years, our primate ancestors evolved from a modest population of sub-Saharan apes into the globally dominant species Homo sapiens. Along the way, humans became incredibly diverse in appearance, language, and culture. How did all of this happen? In The Five-Million-Year Odyssey, Peter Bellwood synthesizes research from archaeology, biology, anthropology, and linguistics to immerse us in the saga of human evolution, from the earliest traces of our hominin forebears in Africa, through waves of human expansion across the continents, and to the rise of agriculture and explosive demographic growth around the world.Bellwood presents our modern diversity as a product of both evolution, which led to the emergence of the genus Homo approximately 2.5 million years ago, and migration, which carried humans into new environments. He introduces us to the ancient hominins—including the australopithecines, Homo erectus, the Neanderthals, and others—before turning to the appearance of Homo sapiens circa 300,000 years ago and subsequent human movement into Eurasia, Australia, and the Americas. Bellwood then explores the invention of agriculture, which enabled farmers to disperse to new territories over the last 10,000 years, facilitating the spread of language families and cultural practices. The outcome is now apparent in our vast array of contemporary ethnicities, linguistic systems, and customs.The fascinating origin story of our varied human existence, The Five-Million-Year Odyssey underscores the importance of recognizing our shared genetic heritage to appreciate what makes us so diverse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aCivilizationxHistory. 0aHuman beingsxMigrations. 0aHuman beingsxOrigin. 0aHuman evolution. 0aLanguage and culturexHistory. 0aLanguage and languagesxOrigin. 0aSocial evolution. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Evolution.2bisacsh  aAcheulean.  aAgriculture (Chinese mythology).  aAgriculture.  aAncient DNA.  aAncient Egypt.  aArchaeological site.  aArchaeology.  aAsceticism.  aAsian people.  aAustralopithecine.  aAustronesian languages.  aBantu languages.  aBody hair.  aBorneo.  aBrain size.  aBronze Age.  aBurial.  aCahokia.  aChert.  